/*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*\
  sprayDryer01_sugar
  ==================

  Single-stage rotary-atomiser spray dryer (PHASE 1).  A 40 wt% sugar
  solution is atomised by a spinning disc and dried by hot air; the water
  evaporates into the air and the sucrose leaves as a fine powder.

  The case ties together everything Choupo has been building toward the
  dryer:

    * the SOLIDS stream model (v0.50): the powder carries a particle-size
      distribution `psd`, not just a flow;
    * the TRANSPORT layer (v0.46 viscosity + v0.52 k & D): the Ranz-Marshall
      drying coefficients h / k_c need the gas viscosity, conductivity and
      water-in-air diffusivity, all computed from the .dat data.

  WHAT YOU SPECIFY (the credo -- hardware + feeds only):
      - the atomiser disc:  wheelDiameter + wheelSpeed
      - the two inlet streams: the sugar solution + the hot drying air

  WHAT THE SIMULATOR COMPUTES (results):
      - exhaust air temperature T_out (adiabatic energy balance)
      - droplet wet-bulb temperature T_wb (psychrometric, Lewis ~ 1)
      - droplet Sauter diameter d32 (Friedman rotary-disc correlation)
        and the powder particle diameter after shrinkage
      - drying kinetics: terminal velocity, Re, Nu/Sh -> h, k_c, and the
        constant-rate drying time of a single droplet

  Order-of-magnitude (computed by the solver, not specified):
      d32 ~ 60 µm  ->  particle ~ 35 µm   (sugar/milk powders: 20-100 µm)
      T_wb ~ 40-50 °C,  T_out ~ 90-100 °C
      h ~ 1000 W/(m²·K),  Re < 1 (Stokes),  τ_drying ~ 0.1 s

  The GAB isotherm + Lewis falling-rate + residence time ARE modelled — see
  the residual-moisture block in the log (X_final ~ 0.014 kg/kg, 1.3 wt%) with a
  real residual moisture in the powder.

  NOTE (slice 4): the atomiser surface tension is NO LONGER a hardcoded
  0.072 N/m constant -- it now comes from the property layer
  (`transport { surfaceTension { model BrockBird; } }`), i.e. sigma(T) of
  the volatile solvent (water) at the feed temperature.  Brock-Bird is a
  generic corresponding-states estimate (it overpredicts H-bonding water,
  ~0.107 vs the hardcoded 0.072 N/m -> d32 60.4 vs 58.1 um).  The golden
  master was deliberately re-recorded against this property-layer sigma(T);
  a spray-dryer case WITHOUT a surfaceTension model falls back to 0.072 and
  stays byte-stable.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

application   choupoSolve;
description   "Spray dryer REA (model chen): Reaction Engineering Approach kinetics -- smooth rate, no critical-moisture break";

verbosity     3;

reports
{
    streamTable    {}
    massBalance    {}
    energyBalance  {}
    profiles       {}        // dumps the powder PSD (massFrac vs diameter)
}
